9. Edge cases

Zero eligible holders at draw → round void, no payout, fees roll into next round's pool (PRINTR keeps them; we just don't claim).
One eligible holder → they win automatically. Still publish randomness for consistency.
Total supply changes mid-round (mint authority active) → just re-read at the next round start. Within a round, use the supply we read at start.
Same-block sell-and-rebuy → handled naturally; the snapshot is read at draw time.
Token decimals → work in raw integer balances internally. Format only at the API boundary.
Process restart mid-round → on boot, compute current round from (now - launchTime) / 15min. If it's a new round, start fresh. If we're mid-round, resume polling.
Process restart between claim and transfer → see §7 failure handling.


10. Transparency surface
For v1, all of these come "for free" from the structure above:

Algorithm published openly (link to a public gist or repo).
Every round in history has the seed used + the full eligible list → anyone can plug them into the formula and reproduce the winner.
Every round has claimTx and payoutTx linking to Solscan.
Be upfront that v1 randomness is server-side (crypto.randomBytes) — the seed is published, but trusting the seed wasn't picked after seeing the eligible list requires trusting us. v2 will move to chain-based randomness.

Add a single static /verify route on the frontend that reads /api/round/:id and walks the user through the math. Nothing fancy — that's covered in the design spec.

11. Build order

Holder fetcher — given a mint, return the eligible list. Standalone script.
Round loop — 15min ticks, snapshots eligible list, picks a random winner with crypto.randomBytes, writes to history.json. No real payouts yet.
HTTP API — wrap the in-memory state in REST endpoints.
Meteora claim integration — install @meteora-ag/dynamic-bonding-curve-sdk, test claimCreatorTradingFee on devnet first, then with tiny mainnet amounts.
Real payouts — wire the transfer step, run end-to-end with a test pool.
Hardening — exclusion list config, restart recovery, basic monitoring.


